I"
<p>Minsky argues that that people have a mechanism for <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/similar-embodiment-predicts-manifold-alignment">predestined learning</a>, which drives us into developing similar <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/concept-learning-is-few-shot-scaffolding-supported-by-working-memory">conceptual frameworks</a>. We might me conditioned to <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/freedom-in-buddhism-is-conditioning-free-mindfulness">be conditioned in certain ways</a>. We might be predisposed to <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/perception-and-motor-action-distort-spatial-representation">a certain kind of perception</a>. In this, predestined learning highlights a middle ground between nature and nurture extremes.</p>
